<subSubSection pageNumber="310" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="310">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">Note:</emphasis>
Burtt (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">Edinburgh J. Bot.</emphasis>
48: 184. 1991) indicated material in the Clifford herbarium as a likely type, but no relevant specimen exists there. The same author subsequently designated a Burman copperplate (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">Rar. Afr. Pl.</emphasis>
1: t. 1. 1738, reproduced by Jarvis in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">Symb. Bot. Upsal.</emphasis>
33(3): 30, f. 5. 2005) as 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
. Unfortunately, this is identifiable, not as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Arctopus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="echinatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">A. echinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but rather as 
<taxonomicName authority="Sonder. Van Wyk" authorityName="Sonder. Van Wyk" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Arctopus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monacanthus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">A. monacanthus</emphasis>
Sonder. Van Wyk
</taxonomicName>
&amp; al. (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">Taxon</emphasis>
55: 541. 2006) therefore proposed the conservation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apiaceae" genus="Arctopus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Apiales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="echinatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="310">A. echinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a conserved type.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
